/* Workplace English Data — Part 2: Emails & Staffroom */
(function() {
  if (typeof WORKPLACE_ENGLISH === 'undefined') return;

  // ============================================================
  // MODULE 2: PROFESSIONAL EMAILS & WRITTEN COMMUNICATION (EXTENDED)
  // ============================================================
  WORKPLACE_ENGLISH.professionalEmails2 = {
    title: "Professional Emails & Written Communication",
    sections: [
      {
        id: "email-openings-closings",
        title: "Email Openings & Closings",
        theory: "Australian workplace emails are friendly but professional. Use first names unless writing to someone you haven't met. 'Hi Sarah' is standard; 'Dear Ms Chen' for formal/first contact. Sign off with 'Kind regards', 'Cheers', or 'Thanks'. Chinese speakers often use overly formal language ('Respected Sir') or skip greetings entirely.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"pe001",type:"fill",q:"___ Rebecca,\n\nI hope you're ___ well.",a:"Hi ... doing",exp:"'Hi [first name]' is the standard greeting for a colleague. 'I hope you're doing well' is warmer and more natural than 'I hope this email finds you well'. Both are fine."},
          {id:"pe002",type:"mc",q:"You are emailing a parent you have never met. Which greeting is most appropriate?",options:["Hey there!","Hi Mrs Thompson,","Dear Mrs Thompson,","G'day Mrs Thompson,"],a:2,exp:"'Dear Mrs Thompson' is correct for a first-contact email to a parent. 'Hi' is too casual for someone you haven't met. 'G'day' is too informal for written communication."},
          {id:"pe003",type:"error",q:"Respected Sir, I am humbly writing to request your kind approval for leave on Monday.",a:"Hi Mark, I'm writing to request leave on Monday.",exp:"'Respected Sir' and 'humbly' are overly formal for Australian workplaces — this style is common in Chinese/South Asian English but sounds out of place. Use the person's first name and keep it direct."},
          {id:"pe004",type:"fill",q:"I'm ___ in touch to let you know about an upcoming change to the ___.",a:"getting ... timetable",exp:"'Getting in touch' is a natural, friendly way to start an email. 'Timetable' is the Australian term (not 'schedule')."},
          {id:"pe005",type:"mc",q:"Which subject line is best for an email about collecting money for a staff gift?",options:["MONEY NEEDED","Staff collection for Karen's farewell — please read","Hey","Important!!!"],a:1,exp:"A good subject line is specific and tells the reader what to expect. Avoid all caps, vague subjects, or excessive punctuation."},
          {id:"pe006",type:"fill",q:"Thanks for your email. I'll ___ back to you by end of ___ with a full response.",a:"get ... day",exp:"'I'll get back to you' = I'll reply. 'By end of day' sets a clear timeline. Acknowledging receipt and setting expectations is professional."},
          {id:"pe007",type:"error",q:"Dear Madam Principal, I want to apply for the position which was advertised. Kindly do the needful.",a:"Dear Ms Harrison, I am writing to apply for the position advertised on the school intranet.",exp:"Use the principal's name, not 'Madam Principal'. 'Kindly do the needful' is Indian English, not used in Australia. Be specific about where you saw the advertisement."},
          {id:"pe008",type:"fill",q:"Just a heads ___ that the Year 10 assembly has been moved to ___.",a:"up ... Wednesday",exp:"'Just a heads up' is an informal way to give advance notice. Very common in Australian workplace emails between colleagues."},
          {id:"pe009",type:"mc",q:"Which closing is appropriate for an email to a parent after a positive phone call?",options:["Later!","Love,","Thanks for the chat today. Kind regards,","Yours faithfully,"],a:2,exp:"'Thanks for the chat today' acknowledges the conversation warmly. 'Kind regards' is the standard professional closing for parents. 'Yours faithfully' is overly formal."},
          {id:"pe010",type:"fill",q:"I ___ to reach out earlier, but it's been a hectic ___.",a:"meant ... week",exp:"'I meant to reach out earlier' is an honest, human way to explain a delayed response. 'Hectic week' is very common in school contexts."},
          {id:"pe011",type:"error",q:"I am writing this email to inform you that please find attached the report.",a:"Please find attached the report I mentioned.",exp:"The original mashes two sentences together. 'I am writing to inform you that' + 'please find attached' should not be in the same clause. Keep it simple and direct."},
          {id:"pe012",type:"mc",q:"When should you use 'Dear Sir/Madam' in an Australian school email?",options:["In every email to be safe","Only when writing to someone whose name you genuinely cannot find","When emailing your principal","When replying to a parent"],a:1,exp:"'Dear Sir/Madam' is only for truly unknown recipients. In schools, you can almost always find someone's name. Using it when the name is available looks lazy or impersonal."},
          {id:"pe013",type:"fill",q:"I hope the school holidays treated you ___. I'm looking ___ to a great Term 2.",a:"well ... forward",exp:"'I hope the holidays treated you well' is a warm post-holiday opener. 'Looking forward to' expresses positive anticipation. Natural start-of-term email language."},
          {id:"pe014",type:"open",q:"Write a brief email to a new parent introducing yourself as their child's teacher.",a:"Dear Mr and Mrs Nguyen,\n\nMy name is Yunshu Gao, and I will be your daughter Linh's Technology teacher this year. I am looking forward to working with her in Year 8.\n\nIf you ever have any questions or concerns, please don't hesitate to get in touch. The best way to reach me is via email, and I usually respond within 24 hours.\n\nKind regards,\nYunshu Gao\nTechnology Teacher\nArthur Phillip High School",exp:"Professional, warm, and informative. Includes your name, the student's name, the subject, and how to contact you. 'Kind regards' is the right level of formality for a first parent email."},
          {id:"pe015",type:"fill",q:"Could you please ___ this to the rest of the team? I want to make sure everyone is in the ___.",a:"forward ... loop",exp:"'Forward this' = send on to others. 'In the loop' = informed/included. Very common Australian workplace idiom."},
          {id:"pe016",type:"error",q:"Hellow, I writting to ask about the meeting time. Plz reply me ASAP.",a:"Hi James, I'm writing to check the meeting time. Could you let me know when you get a chance?",exp:"Multiple errors: 'Hellow' (spelling), 'writting' (double t), 'Plz' (text speak — never in professional emails), 'reply me' (reply to me), 'ASAP' is OK informally but 'when you get a chance' is more collegial."},
          {id:"pe017",type:"mc",q:"What does 'FYI' mean in an email and when is it appropriate?",options:["For Your Information — use in any email","For Your Interest — only for personal topics","For Your Information — when sharing something useful that doesn't require action","Follow Your Instincts — motivational sign-off"],a:2,exp:"FYI = For Your Information. Use it when forwarding or sharing information that doesn't require a reply. It signals 'no action needed from you'. Appropriate between colleagues."},
          {id:"pe018",type:"fill",q:"I wanted to ___ base before the staff meeting tomorrow. Do you have a ___ to chat?",a:"touch ... minute",exp:"'Touch base' = have a quick check-in. 'Do you have a minute?' = are you available for a brief conversation? Casual but professional."},
          {id:"pe019",type:"fill",q:"Thanks for ___ me in on the Year 9 camp details. I'll make sure my class is ___.",a:"filling ... prepared",exp:"'Filling me in' = giving me the information. 'Make sure my class is prepared' shows responsibility. Both are natural colleague-to-colleague phrases."},
          {id:"pe020",type:"error",q:"I regret to inform you that I cannot attend the meeting due to I have class.",a:"Unfortunately, I won't be able to attend the meeting as I have a class at that time.",exp:"'I regret to inform you' is overly formal for a colleague email. 'Due to I have' is grammatically wrong — use 'as' or 'because'. Be specific about the clash."},
          {id:"pe021",type:"mc",q:"A colleague sends you an email with a mistake in your name. What should you do?",options:["Reply angrily correcting them","Ignore it — it's not important","Mention it casually in your reply, e.g., 'Just a heads up — it's Yunshu, not Yanshu!'","Never email them again"],a:2,exp:"A casual, friendly correction is best. Name accuracy matters but it needn't be confrontational. Most people appreciate the correction."},
          {id:"pe022",type:"fill",q:"Apologies for the late ___. I've been snowed ___ with reports this week.",a:"reply ... under",exp:"'Apologies for the late reply' is the standard way to acknowledge a delayed response. 'Snowed under' = very busy/overwhelmed. Common Australian expression."},
          {id:"pe023",type:"fill",q:"I'll be out of the ___ on Friday for a PD day. Please ___ any urgent matters to Sarah.",a:"office ... direct",exp:"'Out of the office' is standard even for teachers (referring to being unavailable). 'Direct matters to Sarah' = send them to Sarah instead."},
          {id:"pe024",type:"error",q:"Dear All Staff, Hereby I am informing you that the photocopier is not working. Please kindly do not use it.",a:"Hi everyone, Just a quick note — the photocopier is out of order. It should be fixed by tomorrow morning.",exp:"'Dear All Staff' is awkward (say 'Hi everyone'). 'Hereby I am informing you' is legal language, not email language. 'Please kindly' is a double softener. Give a solution or timeline."},
          {id:"pe025",type:"mc",q:"When is 'Cheers' an appropriate email sign-off?",options:["In all professional emails","Only when emailing colleagues you know well","When emailing the school board","When making a formal complaint"],a:1,exp:"'Cheers' is perfectly appropriate for colleagues you have an established relationship with. For formal, external, or first-contact emails, use 'Kind regards' instead."},
          {id:"pe026",type:"fill",q:"I'm writing to ___ receipt of your application. We will be in ___ with you shortly.",a:"acknowledge ... touch",exp:"'Acknowledge receipt' = confirm we received it. 'Be in touch with you' = contact you. Formal but warm — good for applicant communication."},
          {id:"pe027",type:"open",q:"Write a brief out-of-office auto-reply for the school holidays.",a:"Thank you for your email. I am currently on school holidays and will have limited access to email until Monday 28 January. If your matter is urgent, please contact the school office on (02) 9635 8200.\n\nI will respond to your email when I return.\n\nKind regards,\nYunshu Gao\nTechnology Teacher\nArthur Phillip High School",exp:"Good auto-replies include: when you'll return, what to do if urgent, and a professional sign-off. Keep it brief and helpful."},
          {id:"pe028",type:"fill",q:"Thanks ___ for organising the professional development session. It was really ___.",a:"heaps ... valuable",exp:"'Thanks heaps' is very Australian and appropriate for colleagues. 'Really valuable' is genuine positive feedback. Natural, warm tone."},
          {id:"pe029",type:"error",q:"With reference to the above mentioned subject, I would like to draw your attention to the matter below.",a:"I wanted to follow up on something we discussed last week.",exp:"Bureaucratic filler. Australian emails should get to the point. 'With reference to the above mentioned subject' says nothing. Replace with what you actually mean."},
          {id:"pe030",type:"mc",q:"You need to email all Year 8 parents about a change to the excursion date. Which subject line is best?",options:["Change","Year 8 excursion — new date: Friday 21 March","IMPORTANT — READ IMMEDIATELY","Update"],a:1,exp:"The subject includes the year group, topic, and the key information (new date). Parents can immediately see what changed without even opening the email."},
          {id:"pe031",type:"fill",q:"Just ___ to confirm that I've booked the computer lab for Period 3 on ___.",a:"writing ... Thursday",exp:"'Just writing to confirm' is a common brief email opener. Confirming bookings in writing creates a record."},
          {id:"pe032",type:"fill",q:"Would you be ___ to covering my Year 7 class during Period 5? I have a ___ with a parent.",a:"open ... meeting",exp:"'Would you be open to' is politer than 'Can you'. 'Covering my class' = teaching it for me. Common teacher-to-teacher request."},
          {id:"pe033",type:"error",q:"I am very sorry to disturb you but I want to ask one small doubt about the timetable.",a:"Sorry to bother you — I have a quick question about the timetable.",exp:"'Disturb' is too strong for a simple email. 'Doubt' means uncertainty/disbelief in Australian English — use 'question'. 'One small doubt' is a common L1 transfer from Mandarin or Hindi."},
          {id:"pe034",type:"mc",q:"What is the best way to address a group email to the whole staff?",options:["Dear Staff Members of the School,","Hi all,","To Whom It May Concern,","Hey guys,"],a:1,exp:"'Hi all' or 'Hi everyone' is the standard Australian group email greeting. 'Dear Staff Members of the School' is too formal. 'Hey guys' is too casual and gendered."},
          {id:"pe035",type:"fill",q:"I'll keep this ___. The deadline for submitting reports is ___ 5pm this Friday.",a:"brief ... by",exp:"'I'll keep this brief' signals a short email. 'By 5pm' sets a clear deadline. Busy teachers appreciate concise emails."}
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "requesting",
        title: "Making Requests & Asking for Help",
        theory: "In Australian workplaces, direct requests are fine but should be softened with modal verbs. 'Could you...', 'Would you mind...', 'I was wondering if...' are all natural. Chinese speakers sometimes make requests too directly ('Give me the file') or too indirectly. The key is matching formality to the relationship.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"pe036",type:"mc",q:"Which is the most appropriate way to ask a colleague for a resource?",options:["Give me the Year 8 worksheet.","I need the Year 8 worksheet now.","Would you mind sharing the Year 8 worksheet when you get a chance?","Can I get that worksheet please."],a:2,exp:"'Would you mind... when you get a chance?' is polite, uses a modal verb, and doesn't pressure. Option D is OK but less polished."},
          {id:"pe037",type:"fill",q:"I was ___ if you could share your unit plan for the ___ topic.",a:"wondering ... sustainability",exp:"'I was wondering if' is the softest request form in English. It sounds tentative and respectful. Perfect for asking colleagues for their materials."},
          {id:"pe038",type:"error",q:"Please to send me the file immediately. I am needing it urgent.",a:"Could you please send me the file? I need it quite urgently.",exp:"No 'to' after 'please' + imperative. 'Am needing' — 'need' is a stative verb (no continuous). 'Urgent' is an adjective; use 'urgently' (adverb). Add a modal to soften."},
          {id:"pe039",type:"fill",q:"___ you be able to swap playground duty with me on ___?",a:"Would ... Tuesday",exp:"'Would you be able to' is a polite request. 'Swap duty' is very common in schools — teachers often exchange supervision responsibilities."},
          {id:"pe040",type:"mc",q:"You need your Head of Department to approve a purchase. Which request is best?",options:["Approve this now please.","I was hoping you could approve this purchase order when you have a moment.","You need to approve this.","I demand approval for this purchase."],a:1,exp:"'I was hoping you could... when you have a moment' is appropriately respectful for someone senior. It's a request, not a demand, and doesn't pressure."},
          {id:"pe041",type:"fill",q:"Do you ___ if I borrow the projector for my Period 4 class? I'll ___ it back by lunch.",a:"mind ... bring",exp:"'Do you mind if I' is a natural, polite request. Adding 'I'll bring it back by lunch' shows consideration and a specific return time."},
          {id:"pe042",type:"error",q:"Can you help me to carry these textbook to the classroom?",a:"Could you help me carry these textbooks to the classroom?",exp:"'Help me carry' (no 'to' — help + bare infinitive). 'Textbooks' needs plural. 'Could' is slightly more polite than 'can' for requests."},
          {id:"pe043",type:"fill",q:"I'd really ___ it if you could proofread my parent newsletter before I ___ it out.",a:"appreciate ... send",exp:"'I'd really appreciate it if' is a warm, grateful request. 'Send it out' = distribute. Asking for proofreading help is perfectly normal in schools."},
          {id:"pe044",type:"mc",q:"A colleague asks 'Would you mind covering my class?' How should you respond if you agree?",options:["I would mind.","No worries at all. What period?","I mind.","Maybe."],a:1,exp:"'No worries at all' is the classic Australian agreement. Note: 'Would you mind?' — 'No' means you agree (no, I don't mind). 'I would mind' means you refuse. This confuses many ESL speakers."},
          {id:"pe045",type:"fill",q:"Sorry to ___ you with this, but could you ___ an eye on my class for five minutes?",a:"bother ... keep",exp:"'Sorry to bother you' acknowledges the imposition. 'Keep an eye on' = watch/supervise briefly. Very common teacher request."},
          {id:"pe046",type:"error",q:"I want you send the report to me before tomorrow.",a:"Would you be able to send me the report by tomorrow?",exp:"'I want you send' is too direct and grammatically wrong (need 'to send'). 'Would you be able to' is much more appropriate for a workplace request."},
          {id:"pe047",type:"fill",q:"Is there any ___ you could print 30 copies of this handout for me? The printer near my room is ___.",a:"chance ... broken",exp:"'Is there any chance you could' is a soft, friendly request. Explaining why (broken printer) makes the request reasonable."},
          {id:"pe048",type:"mc",q:"Your principal asks you to take on extra supervision duty. You want to decline. What is the best response?",options:["No, I'm too busy.","I'd love to help, but I already have three duties this week. Would it be possible to find someone else?","That's not my job.","I suppose I have to, don't I?"],a:1,exp:"Acknowledge the request positively, explain your situation factually, and offer an alternative. This is assertive but professional."},
          {id:"pe049",type:"fill",q:"I was hoping you might be ___ to share your experience with the new ___ platform.",a:"willing ... learning",exp:"'I was hoping you might be willing to' is very soft — multiple hedging layers. Good for asking someone to give up their time or expertise."},
          {id:"pe050",type:"fill",q:"Could I ___ a moment of your time to discuss something about one of my ___?",a:"have ... students",exp:"'Could I have a moment of your time' is a polite way to request a conversation. Specifying the topic (a student) helps the person prioritise."},
          {id:"pe051",type:"error",q:"Excuse me, can you borrow me your stapler? I need to use it.",a:"Excuse me, could I borrow your stapler?",exp:"'Borrow me' is wrong — 'borrow' means to take, 'lend' means to give. Chinese speakers often confuse these (both translate to 借 jiè). Also, 'I need to use it' is redundant."},
          {id:"pe052",type:"mc",q:"Which phrase best softens a follow-up request?",options:["Why haven't you done this yet?","Just a gentle reminder about the reports that are due Friday.","I told you to do this already.","Don't forget!"],a:1,exp:"'Just a gentle reminder' is the gold standard for follow-ups in Australian workplaces. It's polite, non-accusatory, and professional."},
          {id:"pe053",type:"fill",q:"I don't suppose you'd have ___ to help me set up the science lab for ___'s prac?",a:"time ... tomorrow",exp:"'I don't suppose you'd have time' is a very soft negative request — it anticipates 'no' so a 'yes' feels generous. Common British/Australian phrasing."},
          {id:"pe054",type:"open",q:"Write a brief email asking the school librarian to reserve a class set of books for your Year 9 English class.",a:"Hi Michelle,\n\nI was wondering if you could reserve a class set of 'The Absolutely True Diary of a Part-Time Indian' for my Year 9 class? We'll need them from Week 4 to Week 8 this term.\n\nThere are 28 students in the class. If there aren't enough copies, I'm happy to work with what's available.\n\nThanks so much for your help.\n\nCheers,\nYunshu",exp:"Specific request (title, year group, timeline, quantity). 'I was wondering if' is polite. Showing flexibility ('happy to work with what's available') is considerate. 'Cheers' is fine for a colleague."},
          {id:"pe055",type:"fill",q:"Would it be ___ if I left five minutes early today? I have a medical ___ at 4 o'clock.",a:"possible ... appointment",exp:"'Would it be possible if' is very polite. Giving a reason (medical appointment) justifies the request. Direct but respectful."},
          {id:"pe056",type:"error",q:"Please help me. I very need someone assist me with the Year 7 reports.",a:"Could someone give me a hand with the Year 7 reports? I'd really appreciate the help.",exp:"'Very need' is ungrammatical. 'Assist me' is too formal for a staffroom request. 'Give me a hand' is natural Australian English for asking for help."},
          {id:"pe057",type:"fill",q:"I hate to ___, but could you turn down the music in your classroom? It's ___ through the wall.",a:"ask ... coming",exp:"'I hate to ask' softens what could be an awkward request. 'Coming through the wall' describes the problem without accusing."},
          {id:"pe058",type:"mc",q:"You want to ask the IT coordinator to fix your interactive whiteboard. Which is most appropriate?",options:["The board in my room is broken. Fix it.","Hi Alex, when you get a chance, could you take a look at the interactive board in Room 14? It's not responding to touch. No rush — I can work around it today.","My board doesn't work!!!","The technology in this school is terrible. Someone needs to fix my board."],a:1,exp:"Describes the problem specifically, uses 'when you get a chance' and 'no rush' to soften, and mentions a workaround showing you're not helpless."},
          {id:"pe059",type:"fill",q:"I know you're busy, but I'd ___ value your input on this ___.",a:"really ... assessment",exp:"'I know you're busy' acknowledges their workload. 'I'd really value your input' is a flattering way to ask for feedback."},
          {id:"pe060",type:"fill",q:"Is it all ___ if I use your classroom during my ___ period? Mine is being used for exams.",a:"right ... free",exp:"'Is it all right if' is a casual, friendly way to ask permission. 'Free period' = non-teaching period. Common teacher request."},
          {id:"pe061",type:"error",q:"Kindly please revert to me regarding the meeting schedule at your earliest convenient.",a:"Could you let me know about the meeting schedule when you get a chance?",exp:"'Kindly please' is redundant. 'Revert' does not mean 'reply' in Australian English. 'Convenient' should be 'convenience' (noun). The entire sentence is overly formal."},
          {id:"pe062",type:"mc",q:"A casual (relief) teacher asks you where the staffroom is. You're busy. What is the most helpful response?",options:["I'm busy. Ask someone else.","The staffroom is just down the hall on the left — the door with the blue sign. I'd show you but I've got a class. Welcome to the school!","I don't know.","Follow me. I'll take you there right now."],a:1,exp:"Helpful, gives clear directions, explains why you can't do more, and adds a welcome. Option D is generous but impractical if you're heading to class."},
          {id:"pe063",type:"fill",q:"I was hoping to ___ your brains about differentiation strategies for ___.",a:"pick ... maths",exp:"'Pick your brains' = get your expert opinion/ideas. Informal but very common in Australian staffrooms. Shows you value their expertise."},
          {id:"pe064",type:"fill",q:"Any ___ you could email me the staff meeting ___ from last Thursday?",a:"chance ... minutes",exp:"'Any chance you could' is a very casual, friendly request. 'Meeting minutes' = the official record of what was discussed."},
          {id:"pe065",type:"open",q:"Write a brief email to your head teacher requesting a day off for a university exam.",a:"Hi David,\n\nI was hoping to request a day of leave on Friday 14 March for a university exam. It's part of my Master of Teaching degree.\n\nI've prepared a full lesson plan and all resources for my classes that day, so the casual teacher should have everything they need.\n\nPlease let me know if there's a form I need to fill out.\n\nKind regards,\nYunshu",exp:"Clear reason, shows preparation (lesson plans ready), asks about process. 'I was hoping to request' is appropriately polite for someone senior."},
          {id:"pe066",type:"fill",q:"Would you ___ having a quick look at my report comments before I submit them? I'd love a ___ pair of eyes.",a:"mind ... fresh",exp:"'Would you mind having a look' is polite. 'A fresh pair of eyes' = someone new looking at it to catch mistakes. Very common expression."},
          {id:"pe067",type:"error",q:"I must ask you to do me a favour please. Can you help me move the desks?",a:"Could you give me a hand moving the desks?",exp:"'I must ask you to do me a favour' is overly formal and roundabout. In Australian workplaces, just ask directly but politely. 'Give me a hand' is natural."},
          {id:"pe068",type:"fill",q:"Sorry to chase this ___, but I still haven't received the ___ I requested last week.",a:"up ... resources",exp:"'Sorry to chase this up' is the polite way to follow up on an unfulfilled request. 'Chase up' = follow up on. Very Australian."},
          {id:"pe069",type:"mc",q:"You need to ask the office staff to print something urgently. Which approach is best?",options:["Print this NOW.","Hi Linda, I'm really sorry for the short notice, but could you print 25 copies of this for my Period 3 class? I know it's a pain — I owe you one!","I need printing.","You need to print something for me."],a:1,exp:"Acknowledges the inconvenience, gives specifics, shows appreciation. 'I owe you one' is a friendly Australian way of saying 'I'll return the favour'."},
          {id:"pe070",type:"fill",q:"I don't want to ___ on your toes, but I think we might need to ___ our approach to this unit.",a:"step ... rethink",exp:"'Step on your toes' = overstep boundaries or offend. Prefacing with this shows awareness. 'Rethink our approach' is constructive, not critical."}
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "parent-communication",
        title: "Communicating with Parents",
        theory: "Parent emails require extra care. Be specific about behaviour or academic concerns, use the 'positive-concern-action' sandwich, avoid jargon, and always end with an invitation to discuss further. Remember parents may not understand educational terminology.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"pe071",type:"fill",q:"Dear Mr and Mrs ___, \n\nI am writing to share some positive news about ___'s progress in Technology this term.",a:"Patel ... Arjun",exp:"Use the family name for parent greetings. Always name the student specifically. Starting with positive news builds goodwill."},
          {id:"pe072",type:"mc",q:"Which sentence best describes a behaviour concern to a parent?",options:["Your son is always disruptive and rude.","I've noticed that Jake has been finding it challenging to stay focused during independent work time over the past two weeks.","Jake is naughty in class.","Your child has behavioural issues."],a:1,exp:"Specific (independent work time), time-bound (two weeks), objective (finding it challenging), and non-judgemental. Avoids labels like 'naughty' or 'rude'."},
          {id:"pe073",type:"error",q:"Your daughter she is not doing good in my class. She need to try more harder.",a:"I wanted to let you know that I have some concerns about Emma's progress in Science. She has been finding the recent topic quite challenging.",exp:"'Your daughter she' is a double subject (Chinese L1 pattern). 'Not doing good' should be 'not doing well'. 'More harder' is a double comparative. Also, be specific and constructive."},
          {id:"pe074",type:"fill",q:"I wanted to ___ you know about a concern I have regarding ___'s engagement in class.",a:"let ... Sophie",exp:"'Let you know about a concern' is gentle and professional. Using the student's name makes it personal and specific."},
          {id:"pe075",type:"mc",q:"Which is the best way to end a parent email about a behaviour concern?",options:["I hope you will punish him at home.","I'm confident that with our combined support, we can help Liam get back on track.","This is your problem to fix.","There is nothing more I can do."],a:1,exp:"'Combined support' emphasises partnership. 'Get back on track' is positive and future-focused. Never suggest punishment or shift all responsibility to parents."},
          {id:"pe076",type:"fill",q:"I have ___ that Chloe's homework completion has ___ significantly over the past three weeks.",a:"noticed ... dropped",exp:"'I have noticed that' reports an observation. 'Dropped significantly' gives measurable detail. 'Over the past three weeks' provides a timeframe."},
          {id:"pe077",type:"error",q:"Dear Parent, Your child he absent many time this month. This is not acceptable.",a:"Dear Mrs Wilson, I'm writing to discuss Aiden's attendance this month. He has been absent on five occasions, and I'm concerned he may be falling behind in his classwork.",exp:"Use the parent's name. 'He absent' needs 'has been'. 'Many time' needs 'many times'. 'Not acceptable' is accusatory — express concern instead."},
          {id:"pe078",type:"fill",q:"I'm pleased to let you know that Isabella received a ___ award at this week's assembly for her outstanding ___ in class.",a:"merit ... effort",exp:"Sharing positive news strengthens the parent-teacher relationship. 'Merit award' is common in Australian schools. Be specific about why."},
          {id:"pe079",type:"mc",q:"A parent emails you angrily about a grade. What is the best first step?",options:["Reply immediately defending yourself.","Wait at least an hour, re-read their email calmly, acknowledge their concern, and offer to meet.","Ignore the email.","Forward it to the principal."],a:1,exp:"Never reply in the heat of the moment. Acknowledge feelings, explain your perspective calmly, and offer a face-to-face meeting where complex issues are better resolved."},
          {id:"pe080",type:"fill",q:"Would you be ___ to come in for a brief meeting to discuss ___'s learning? I have some suggestions that may ___.",a:"available ... Oliver ... help",exp:"'Would you be available' is polite. Mentioning 'suggestions that may help' signals you have solutions, not just complaints."},
          {id:"pe081",type:"error",q:"I want to inform you that your son fail the exam. He is not study enough.",a:"I'm writing to discuss the results of the recent assessment. Unfortunately, Thomas did not achieve a passing grade. I would like to work with you and Thomas to develop a plan to improve his results.",exp:"'Fail the exam' is too blunt and lacks support. 'Is not study' needs 'is not studying' or 'has not been studying'. Frame results constructively with a forward plan."},
          {id:"pe082",type:"fill",q:"Thank you for ___ the time to speak with me today. As discussed, we've agreed on the following ___ steps...",a:"taking ... action",exp:"Following up a meeting in writing creates a record. 'As discussed' references the conversation. 'Action steps' = agreed next actions."},
          {id:"pe083",type:"mc",q:"What does the 'positive-concern-action' sandwich look like in a parent email?",options:["Positive news, then complaint, then threat","Start with a strength, describe the concern, then outline the plan to address it","Three positives and no concerns","Action, concern, positive"],a:1,exp:"The sandwich: (1) Start positive — what the child does well. (2) Describe the concern specifically. (3) What you plan to do and how the parent can help. This is the gold standard."},
          {id:"pe084",type:"fill",q:"Zara is a ___ and enthusiastic member of the class. However, I've noticed she has been ___ to complete her assignments on time recently.",a:"valued ... struggling",exp:"Positive start ('valued and enthusiastic'), then the concern ('struggling to complete'). 'Struggling' is non-judgemental — it implies difficulty, not laziness."},
          {id:"pe085",type:"open",q:"Write a parent email using the positive-concern-action sandwich about a student who talks too much in class.",a:"Dear Mr and Mrs Hassan,\n\nI hope you're well. I wanted to touch base about Youssef's progress in Technology.\n\nFirstly, Youssef is a wonderful contributor to class discussions. He has great ideas and isn't afraid to share them, which I really value.\n\nHowever, I've noticed that he sometimes finds it hard to stop chatting during independent work time. This means he isn't always completing his tasks, and it can distract the students around him.\n\nI've moved his seat to reduce distractions and I'm giving him a visual reminder card. It would be great if you could chat with him about staying focused during quiet work time.\n\nPlease don't hesitate to get in touch if you'd like to discuss this further.\n\nKind regards,\nYunshu Gao",exp:"Perfect sandwich: positive (great contributor), concern (talking during independent work — specific), action (seat change, visual reminder, parent support). Tone is collaborative, not accusatory."},
          {id:"pe086",type:"fill",q:"We are holding parent-teacher ___ on Thursday 20 March from 3:30 to 6:00 pm. Please book a time ___ that suits you.",a:"interviews ... slot",exp:"'Parent-teacher interviews' is the Australian term (not 'conferences'). 'Book a time slot' = reserve an appointment."},
          {id:"pe087",type:"error",q:"Kindly note that your daughter will be punish if she continue to not submit homework.",a:"I wanted to let you know that if Mia continues to have difficulty submitting homework, there may be consequences as outlined in the school policy. I'd like to work with you to find a solution before it reaches that point.",exp:"'Will be punish' — passive needs 'punished'. 'Continue to not submit' — awkward; 'continues to have difficulty submitting' is better. Focus on solutions, not threats."},
          {id:"pe088",type:"fill",q:"I am ___ to invite you to our annual showcase evening, where students will be ___ their Term 1 projects.",a:"pleased ... presenting",exp:"'Pleased to invite you' is warm and professional. 'Showcase evening' is a community engagement event. Naming what students will present builds excitement."},
          {id:"pe089",type:"mc",q:"A parent writes: 'My daughter says you're unfair.' How should you respond?",options:["Your daughter is lying.","I'm sorry to hear that Lily feels that way. I'd like to understand her concerns better. Would you be available for a phone call or meeting so we can discuss this?","I treat all students fairly. End of discussion.","I'll ask the other students if they think I'm fair."],a:1,exp:"Acknowledge the feeling without admitting fault. Offer to discuss further. Using the student's name shows care. Moving to a phone call or meeting prevents email escalation."},
          {id:"pe090",type:"fill",q:"As we approach the end of ___, I wanted to give you a brief summary of ___'s progress and areas for growth.",a:"term ... Daniel",exp:"End-of-term progress updates are expected. 'Areas for growth' is the positive way to say 'weaknesses' in educational contexts."},
          {id:"pe091",type:"error",q:"I am very satisfy with your child progress. He is a very good student always.",a:"I am very pleased with James's progress this term. He consistently demonstrates a positive attitude and strong work ethic.",exp:"'Satisfy' should be 'satisfied' (adjective). 'Child progress' needs possessive. 'Good student always' has awkward word order. Be specific about what makes them good."},
          {id:"pe092",type:"fill",q:"If you have any questions or ___, please don't ___ to get in touch.",a:"concerns ... hesitate",exp:"'Questions or concerns' covers both information needs and worries. 'Don't hesitate to get in touch' is the standard invitation phrase in parent emails."},
          {id:"pe093",type:"mc",q:"You need to inform parents about a head lice outbreak. Which tone is appropriate?",options:["Disgusting head lice found in your child's class!","We are writing to let you know that head lice have been detected in our class. Please check your child's hair tonight and treat if necessary.","Someone in your class has nits. Check your kids.","This is a matter of hygiene and you should be ashamed."],a:1,exp:"Factual, non-shaming, specific about what parents should do. Head lice are common in primary and secondary schools. Never identify the affected child."},
          {id:"pe094",type:"fill",q:"I appreciate your ___ in this matter. Working together will help ensure the best ___ for your child.",a:"support ... outcome",exp:"'Appreciate your support' and 'best outcome for your child' are standard partnership-building phrases in parent communication."},
          {id:"pe095",type:"open",q:"Write a brief email to a parent about their child receiving a school award.",a:"Dear Mrs Chen,\n\nI am delighted to let you know that Lily has been selected to receive a Technology Excellence Award at next week's assembly.\n\nLily has consistently produced outstanding work this term, and her design portfolio was one of the best in the year group. She should be very proud of her achievement.\n\nThe assembly will be held on Wednesday 19 March at 9:15 a.m. in the school hall. You are most welcome to attend.\n\nKind regards,\nYunshu Gao\nTechnology Teacher",exp:"Specific (which award, why, when, where). Invites the parent. Uses the student's name. 'Most welcome to attend' is warm and formal enough."},
          {id:"pe096",type:"fill",q:"I understand this may be ___ to hear, but I believe it's important that we work together to ___ the issue early.",a:"difficult ... address",exp:"'I understand this may be difficult to hear' shows empathy. 'Address the issue early' = deal with it before it gets worse. Collaborative language."},
          {id:"pe097",type:"error",q:"Regarding to your son, I must say that his academic is not satisfy. Please take necessary action.",a:"I wanted to discuss your son Marcus's academic progress with you. I have noticed he has been finding the recent topics quite challenging, and I'd like to suggest some strategies to help.",exp:"'Regarding to' — no 'to' needed. 'His academic is not satisfy' — 'academic performance is not satisfactory'. 'Take necessary action' is vague and bureaucratic."},
          {id:"pe098",type:"fill",q:"I'm writing to let you know that we'll be starting a new ___ next week on digital technologies. Students will need to ___ a USB drive.",a:"unit ... bring",exp:"Informing parents about new units and required materials is good practice. 'Unit' is the Australian term for a topic/module of work."},
          {id:"pe099",type:"mc",q:"What jargon should you avoid in parent emails?",options:["Student's name","'Your child has not met the Stage 4 NESA outcomes for syllabus dot point 4.1.2'","The subject name","The school name"],a:1,exp:"Parents don't understand syllabus codes and outcome numbers. Say 'Your child is finding it challenging to analyse data in Science' instead. Always translate jargon into plain English."},
          {id:"pe100",type:"fill",q:"I wanted to ___ you that your son has been selected for the inter-school debating ___.",a:"congratulate ... team",exp:"Sharing good news builds the relationship. 'Congratulate you' (the parents) makes them feel proud. 'Inter-school' = between schools."},
          {id:"pe101",type:"error",q:"We would like to inform you that the school will be close early tomorrow due to teacher training.",a:"We would like to let you know that the school will be closing early tomorrow for a staff professional development day.",exp:"'Close' should be 'closing'. 'Teacher training' is less professional than 'staff professional development day'. 'Let you know' is more natural than 'inform you' for school-to-parent communication."},
          {id:"pe102",type:"fill",q:"Please be ___ that this email contains sensitive information about your child and should be treated as ___.",a:"aware ... confidential",exp:"'Please be aware' for sensitive content. 'Treated as confidential' reminds parents not to share. Important for welfare or disciplinary matters."},
          {id:"pe103",type:"fill",q:"I'd like to ___ a meeting to discuss the best way to ___ your daughter's needs in the classroom.",a:"arrange ... support",exp:"'Arrange a meeting' is professional. 'Support your daughter's needs' is positive, student-centred language. Shows you are proactive."},
          {id:"pe104",type:"mc",q:"A parent requests that their child not sit next to a particular student. What is the best response?",options:["I'll move them immediately — parents know best.","Thank you for raising this. I'll look into the seating arrangements and see what I can do. I always aim to create a positive learning environment for all students.","That's none of your business — I decide the seating plan.","I'll move the other child instead."],a:1,exp:"Acknowledges the concern, doesn't make promises, and frames it around all students' learning. You maintain professional authority while being responsive."},
          {id:"pe105",type:"fill",q:"Your daughter has made ___ progress this term. Her confidence in presenting to the class has ___ significantly.",a:"excellent ... grown",exp:"Specific positive feedback with evidence. 'Grown significantly' shows measurable improvement in a specific skill."}
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "reporting-updates",
        title: "Reports & Updates to Colleagues",
        theory: "Professional updates to colleagues should be concise and action-oriented. Use dot points for clarity. Start with the key message, then provide details. The Australian workplace values brevity — if it can be said in 3 sentences, don't write a paragraph.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"pe106",type:"fill",q:"Hi team,\n\nJust a quick ___ from today's Year 8 ___.",a:"update ... excursion",exp:"'Quick update' signals brevity. Naming the specific event gives context immediately."},
          {id:"pe107",type:"mc",q:"Which is the best structure for a meeting summary email?",options:["A long paragraph covering everything discussed","Key decisions in dot points, action items with names and deadlines, and next meeting date","Just 'Good meeting today — chat later!'","A detailed transcript of everything said"],a:1,exp:"Dot points for decisions, clear action items with owners and deadlines, and the next meeting date. Busy colleagues need to scan quickly."},
          {id:"pe108",type:"error",q:"The meeting was held and many thing were discuss. We decide to change the assessment.",a:"At today's meeting, we discussed several items and decided to revise the Year 9 assessment task. Key changes are outlined below.",exp:"Passive, vague opening. 'Thing' needs plural. 'Discuss' needs 'discussed'. 'Decide' needs 'decided'. 'The assessment' — which one? Be specific."},
          {id:"pe109",type:"fill",q:"Action items from today's faculty meeting:\n• Sarah — update the ___ plan by Friday\n• James — book the computer lab for Week ___",a:"assessment ... 6",exp:"Action items need: who, what, when. Dot points make them scannable. This is the standard format in Australian schools."},
          {id:"pe110",type:"fill",q:"I wanted to ___ the team know that I've completed the risk assessment for the Year 10 ___ to Taronga Zoo.",a:"let ... excursion",exp:"'Let the team know' is natural for sharing information. 'Excursion to Taronga Zoo' — specific and factual."},
          {id:"pe111",type:"mc",q:"When reporting a student welfare concern to the wellbeing team, what is most important?",options:["Your personal opinion about the family","Specific observable behaviours with dates and examples","A diagnosis of the student's condition","What other students have told you about them"],a:1,exp:"Report what you observe (behaviour, frequency, dates), not what you assume. Never diagnose. Second-hand information should be clearly labelled as such."},
          {id:"pe112",type:"error",q:"I am writing to let everyone know that the assembly it will be postpone to next Monday.",a:"Just a heads up — the assembly has been postponed to next Monday.",exp:"'The assembly it' — double subject. 'Postpone' needs passive 'postponed'. Overly formal opening for a quick admin update. 'Heads up' is natural for colleagues."},
          {id:"pe113",type:"fill",q:"For the ___ of colleagues who weren't at the meeting, here's a brief ___.",a:"benefit ... summary",exp:"'For the benefit of' is a polite way to justify sharing information. 'Brief summary' sets expectations for length."},
          {id:"pe114",type:"fill",q:"The NAPLAN results ___ that our Year 7 cohort is performing above the national ___ in reading.",a:"indicate ... average",exp:"'Results indicate' is evidence-based language. 'National average' is the benchmark. NAPLAN is Australia's national literacy and numeracy assessment."},
          {id:"pe115",type:"mc",q:"What does 'KPI' stand for in a professional context?",options:["Key Personal Information","Keep Preparing Immediately","Key Performance Indicator","Kids' Progress Index"],a:2,exp:"KPI = Key Performance Indicator. Schools use KPIs to track measurable goals such as attendance rates, literacy levels, and student engagement."},
          {id:"pe116",type:"fill",q:"I've ___ together a brief handover document for anyone covering my classes next ___.",a:"put ... week",exp:"'Put together' = prepared/compiled. Handover documents help casual teachers teach your classes effectively."},
          {id:"pe117",type:"error",q:"Hereby I would like to bring to your attention that the projector in Room 15 is not function properly.",a:"Just letting you know — the projector in Room 15 isn't working properly. Could someone from IT take a look?",exp:"'Hereby I would like to bring to your attention' is bureaucratic. 'Not function' needs 'not functioning'. Add a clear request for action."},
          {id:"pe118",type:"fill",q:"As ___ at the staff meeting, the new behaviour management policy will take ___ from Week 3.",a:"discussed ... effect",exp:"'As discussed' references a prior agreement. 'Take effect from' = start being implemented. Formal but clear."},
          {id:"pe119",type:"open",q:"Write a brief email updating your head of department on how a challenging class is going.",a:"Hi Sarah,\n\nQuick update on Year 9 Period 5 — things are improving. Since we introduced the new seating plan and the structured lesson routine, off-task behaviour has dropped noticeably.\n\nTwo students (Jayden and Cooper) are still finding it hard to stay focused, so I'm trialling individual behaviour contracts with them this week.\n\nOverall, I'm feeling more confident with the group. Thanks for your support — the strategies you suggested have really helped.\n\nCheers,\nYunshu",exp:"Honest, specific, acknowledges improvement and ongoing challenges. Names specific strategies. Thanks the person who helped. 'Cheers' for a close colleague."},
          {id:"pe120",type:"fill",q:"Please ___ that the Year 8 assessment deadline has been ___ to Friday 28 March.",a:"note ... extended",exp:"'Please note' is standard for formal announcements. 'Extended to' means the deadline moved later."},
          {id:"pe121",type:"mc",q:"When should you CC your head of department on a parent email?",options:["On every single email","When the issue involves a formal complaint, serious behaviour, or when you want a record of the communication","Never — it's your classroom","Only when the parent asks"],a:1,exp:"CC your HoD on serious or formal matters. This creates a record and ensures your supervisor is aware. Routine positive emails don't need it."},
          {id:"pe122",type:"fill",q:"I'm ___ to report that the Year 7 STEM day was a great success. Student feedback has been overwhelmingly ___.",a:"pleased ... positive",exp:"'Pleased to report' is professional and enthusiastic. 'Overwhelmingly positive' conveys strong results."},
          {id:"pe123",type:"error",q:"All of teacher should to attend the training on Monday. It is a must.",a:"All teachers are required to attend the training session on Monday.",exp:"'All of teacher' — 'All teachers' (no 'of', plural). 'Should to attend' — no 'to' after modal. 'It is a must' is informal — 'are required to' is professional."},
          {id:"pe124",type:"fill",q:"I've identified a ___ with the current assessment task. I'd like to ___ some modifications at the next meeting.",a:"concern ... propose",exp:"'Identified a concern' is diplomatic. 'Propose modifications' is constructive — you're not just complaining, you have solutions."},
          {id:"pe125",type:"fill",q:"The professional development workshop on ___ literacy strategies was very informative. Key ___ included...",a:"digital ... takeaways",exp:"'Key takeaways' = most important points learned. Sharing PD learnings with colleagues is valued in Australian schools."},
          {id:"pe126",type:"mc",q:"You need to report that a student was injured during a practical lesson. What must you do?",options:["Email the principal immediately but casually","Complete an official incident report with factual details, notify the relevant coordinator, and inform the parents","Tell the student to walk it off","Post about it in the staff WhatsApp group"],a:1,exp:"Incident reports are legal documents. They must be factual, detailed, and submitted through official channels. Parents must be notified. This is a duty of care obligation."},
          {id:"pe127",type:"fill",q:"I'm ___ this to confirm that the Year 10 work experience placement dates have been ___ by the coordinator.",a:"writing ... confirmed",exp:"Written confirmation creates a record. 'Confirmed by the coordinator' = officially approved. Important for excursions and external activities."},
          {id:"pe128",type:"error",q:"FYI, the new policy about mobile phone will start from next term. Please make sure to follow.",a:"FYI — the new mobile phone policy will take effect from next term. Please ensure you are familiar with the details and enforce it consistently.",exp:"'Mobile phone' needs plural context or 'mobile phone use'. 'Start from' is less professional than 'take effect from'. 'Make sure to follow' is vague — follow what?"},
          {id:"pe129",type:"fill",q:"Could everyone please ___ their class rolls by the end of the day? Attendance data is due to the ___ office tomorrow.",a:"submit ... front",exp:"'Submit class rolls' is a routine admin task. 'Front office' = school administration office. Clear deadline and reason."},
          {id:"pe130",type:"open",q:"Write a brief handover note for a colleague who will be teaching your Year 7 class while you attend a workshop.",a:"Hi Priya,\n\nThanks for covering my Year 7 Technology class (Period 3, Room 14).\n\nThe lesson is set up on the class computer — open the PowerPoint on the desktop called 'L12-Bridges.pptx'. Students know the routine:\n\n1. Silent reading of the design brief (5 mins)\n2. Group work on their bridge prototypes (25 mins)\n3. Clean-up and reflection journal entry (10 mins)\n\nSeating plan is on the wall. Keep an eye on table 3 — they can get a bit loud. If anything comes up, Mr Peters in Room 12 is happy to help.\n\nThanks heaps!\nYunshu",exp:"Includes: room number, lesson plan location, student routine, timing, seating plan, behaviour notes, and emergency contact. Clear, practical, and appreciative."},
          {id:"pe131",type:"fill",q:"The ___ data from last term shows a 12% increase in student ___ across all year groups.",a:"attendance ... participation",exp:"Data-driven reporting with specific percentages. 'Across all year groups' shows the trend is school-wide."},
          {id:"pe132",type:"fill",q:"I'd like to ___ an item to the agenda for next week's meeting. I think we need to discuss ___.",a:"add ... differentiation",exp:"'Add an item to the agenda' is how you request to discuss something at a meeting. Be specific about the topic."},
          {id:"pe133",type:"mc",q:"What is a 'duty of care' in an Australian school context?",options:["A type of homework","The legal obligation to take reasonable steps to protect students from foreseeable harm","A cleaning roster","An optional responsibility"],a:1,exp:"Duty of care is a legal obligation for all Australian teachers. It means taking reasonable steps to ensure student safety and wellbeing at all times during school activities."},
          {id:"pe134",type:"fill",q:"Following on from our conversation, I've ___ the updated scope and sequence. The main changes are ___ in yellow.",a:"attached ... highlighted",exp:"'Following on from' connects to a prior discussion. 'Highlighted in yellow' makes changes easy to find. Practical and considerate."},
          {id:"pe135",type:"error",q:"The result of the survey is show that most of student are satisfy with the new system.",a:"The survey results show that most students are satisfied with the new system.",exp:"'Result' needs plural 'results'. 'Is show' should be 'show'. 'Most of student' should be 'most students'. 'Satisfy' should be 'satisfied'."},
          {id:"pe136",type:"fill",q:"Just a ___ — the photocopier will be out of ___ on Thursday for maintenance.",a:"reminder ... service",exp:"'Just a reminder' is a standard heads-up format. 'Out of service' = not working/unavailable. Practical administrative communication."},
          {id:"pe137",type:"fill",q:"I've been trialling a new ___ strategy with my Year 8 class and the early ___ are promising.",a:"teaching ... results",exp:"'Trialling a new strategy' shows professional growth. 'Early results are promising' is cautiously optimistic — appropriate for ongoing work."},
          {id:"pe138",type:"mc",q:"You discover a student has been self-harming. What is the correct reporting procedure?",options:["Email the parents immediately","Tell the student to stop","Notify the school counsellor or wellbeing team immediately, following mandatory reporting procedures","Post about it in the staff chat"],a:2,exp:"Self-harm requires immediate referral to the wellbeing team. Teachers are mandatory reporters in NSW. Do not contact parents yourself — the counsellor will guide that process."},
          {id:"pe139",type:"fill",q:"Thank you to everyone who ___ to the successful Open Day. The feedback from families was ___.",a:"contributed ... fantastic",exp:"Acknowledging team effort is important. 'Contributed to' recognises individual roles. 'Feedback was fantastic' celebrates collective success."},
          {id:"pe140",type:"fill",q:"I'm ___ out to see if anyone has experience with the new online ___ platform the school has adopted.",a:"reaching ... reporting",exp:"'Reaching out' = contacting. Asking for help from colleagues shows professional humility and builds collaboration."}
        ]
      }
    ]
  };

  // ============================================================
  // MODULE 3: STAFFROOM SMALL TALK & SOCIAL ENGLISH
  // ============================================================
  WORKPLACE_ENGLISH.staffroomTalk = {
    title: "Staffroom Small Talk & Social English",
    sections: [
      {
        id: "greetings-openers",
        title: "Greetings & Conversation Openers",
        theory: "Australian staffroom culture values casual friendliness. 'How's it going?', 'How was your weekend?', 'Busy day?' are standard openers. Chinese speakers often feel uncertain about when and how to initiate conversation. The key is to keep it light and show genuine interest.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"st001",type:"fill",q:"Morning, Karen! How's it ___? Ready for another ___ day?",a:"going ... big",exp:"'How's it going?' is the most common Australian greeting. 'Ready for another big day?' is a light, friendly opener that acknowledges the day ahead."},
          {id:"st002",type:"mc",q:"A colleague walks into the staffroom and says 'How are ya?' What is the most natural response?",options:["I am fine, thank you. And you?","Good thanks! How about you?","I am experiencing a state of general wellbeing.","Not bad, not bad."],a:1,exp:"'Good thanks! How about you?' is natural and reciprocates. Option D is also fine but less engaged. Option A is grammatically correct but sounds stiff in a casual Australian staffroom."},
          {id:"st003",type:"fill",q:"Hey Tom! How was your ___? Did you get up to ___?",a:"weekend ... much",exp:"'How was your weekend?' is the standard Monday opener. 'Did you get up to much?' = Did you do anything interesting? Very Australian."},
          {id:"st004",type:"error",q:"I am fine thank you. And yourself? I wish you have a good day.",a:"Good thanks! Yeah, not bad. Hope you have a great day!",exp:"'I am fine thank you' is too formal for the staffroom. 'I wish you have' should be 'I hope you have'. Natural Australian: 'Good thanks' or 'Yeah, not bad'."},
          {id:"st005",type:"mc",q:"Which is the most natural way to start a conversation with a colleague you see every day?",options:["Greetings and salutations, colleague.","Hey! Busy morning?","I would like to formally acknowledge your presence.","Good morning. I trust you are well."],a:1,exp:"'Hey! Busy morning?' is perfectly natural for a daily colleague interaction. Short, casual, and invites a response."},
          {id:"st006",type:"fill",q:"Long time no ___! How have you ___? I haven't seen you in ages.",a:"see ... been",exp:"'Long time no see' is a common informal greeting when you haven't seen someone for a while. 'How have you been?' asks about their general wellbeing over that period."},
          {id:"st007",type:"fill",q:"___ day today, isn't it? I've been flat ___ since Period 1.",a:"Crazy ... out",exp:"'Crazy day' is a common opener. 'Flat out' is very Australian — it means extremely busy. Natural staffroom conversation starter."},
          {id:"st008",type:"mc",q:"What does 'How's things?' mean?",options:["How much do you own?","How is your general situation/life?","What are you doing right now?","How many things do you have?"],a:1,exp:"'How's things?' (informal, grammatically loose) is a casual Australian greeting meaning 'How is everything going in your life/work?' It's interchangeable with 'How's it going?'"},
          {id:"st009",type:"error",q:"Good morning teacher. How do you do? I hope your health is good.",a:"Morning, Sarah! How's it going? Good weekend?",exp:"'Teacher' is not used as an address term in Australian staffrooms — use the person's name. 'How do you do?' is archaic. 'I hope your health is good' is overly formal."},
          {id:"st010",type:"fill",q:"Happy ___! Nearly there — just one more ___ to go.",a:"Friday ... lesson",exp:"TGIF culture is alive in schools. 'Nearly there' = almost at the end. 'One more lesson to go' is relatable for every teacher."},
          {id:"st011",type:"fill",q:"You look like you could use a ___. Rough ___?",a:"coffee ... morning",exp:"'You look like you could use a coffee' is a sympathetic, friendly observation. 'Rough morning?' invites them to share without prying."},
          {id:"st012",type:"mc",q:"A new teacher joins the staffroom. What is the best way to make them feel welcome?",options:["Wait for them to speak first","Say 'Hey, I'm Yunshu — I teach Tech. Welcome to the team! Want a coffee?'","Formally introduce yourself with a handshake and business card","Ignore them until they prove themselves"],a:1,exp:"Casual, warm, name + subject, offer of hospitality. This is the Australian way. A formal handshake with a business card would feel strange in a staffroom."},
          {id:"st013",type:"fill",q:"How did your Year 9s go today? Mine were absolutely ___. Must be something in the ___.",a:"feral ... water",exp:"'Feral' is Australian slang for wild/badly behaved. 'Must be something in the water' is a humorous way to say there's no logical explanation. Classic staffroom commiseration."},
          {id:"st014",type:"error",q:"How is your today? Are you busy or free?",a:"How's your day going? Busy?",exp:"'How is your today' is grammatically wrong — 'How's your day going?' is correct. 'Are you busy or free?' is too direct/binary. Just 'Busy?' is natural."},
          {id:"st015",type:"fill",q:"I can't believe it's only ___. This week is ___ forever.",a:"Tuesday ... dragging",exp:"'I can't believe it's only Tuesday' is a classic mid-week complaint. 'Dragging forever' = passing very slowly. Relatable staffroom talk."},
          {id:"st016",type:"open",q:"Write a natural staffroom conversation starter for a Monday morning with a colleague you know well.",a:"Morning, Priya! How was your weekend? Do anything fun? I spent mine trying to finish my Year 10 reports — so riveting! Did you manage to get any marking done or did you actually enjoy yourself?",exp:"Casual, warm, self-deprecating humour about marking is very relatable for teachers. Asking a follow-up question shows genuine interest."},
          {id:"st017",type:"fill",q:"What are you ___ for lunch? I'm thinking of grabbing something from the ___ down the road.",a:"having ... cafe",exp:"Discussing lunch is classic staffroom small talk. 'Grabbing something' = getting food quickly. Casual and friendly."},
          {id:"st018",type:"mc",q:"What does 'TGIF' mean?",options:["Teachers Get Incredibly Frustrated","Thank God It's Friday","The Greatest Is First","This Goes In Files"],a:1,exp:"TGIF = Thank God It's Friday. Widely used in Australian workplaces to express relief that the working week is almost over."},
          {id:"st019",type:"fill",q:"Is it just me, or is it absolutely ___ outside? I'm melting in my ___.",a:"boiling ... classroom",exp:"Talking about the weather is a universal Australian conversation starter. 'Absolutely boiling' = very hot. 'Melting' is hyperbolic and relatable."},
          {id:"st020",type:"fill",q:"How's your new class going? Are they ___ in yet, or still testing the ___?",a:"settling ... boundaries",exp:"'Settling in' = getting used to the routine. 'Testing the boundaries' = pushing the limits to see what they can get away with. Start-of-term teacher talk."},
          {id:"st021",type:"error",q:"Teacher Karen, I want to talk you about something. You are free now?",a:"Hey Karen, have you got a sec? I wanted to chat about something.",exp:"Don't call colleagues 'Teacher'. 'Talk you' needs 'talk to you'. 'You are free now?' should be 'Have you got a sec?' (very Australian for 'are you available?')."},
          {id:"st022",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'Not bad' when you ask how they are. What does this mean?",options:["They are feeling terrible","They are doing fine — it's a neutral-to-positive response","They are angry at you","They need help"],a:1,exp:"'Not bad' is Australian understatement for 'I'm doing OK' or even 'I'm doing well'. It's neutral-to-positive. Don't take it as negative."},
          {id:"st023",type:"fill",q:"Did you ___ the email about the new playground ___? Sounds like a nightmare.",a:"see ... roster",exp:"'Did you see the email?' is a natural way to bring up a shared topic. Commenting on it ('sounds like a nightmare') invites discussion."},
          {id:"st024",type:"fill",q:"I heard you're running the school ___ this year. That's a big ___!",a:"musical ... job",exp:"'That's a big job' is a respectful way to acknowledge someone's extra workload. It validates their commitment."},
          {id:"st025",type:"mc",q:"What does 'flat out like a lizard drinking' mean?",options:["Lying flat on the ground","Extremely relaxed","Extremely busy","Drinking too much water"],a:2,exp:"This is a classic Australian expression meaning 'very busy'. It paints a picture of a lizard lying flat to drink water — i.e., going as fast as possible. Used humorously."},
          {id:"st026",type:"fill",q:"You're looking ___ today! Did something good happen, or did you just get a good night's ___?",a:"bright ... sleep",exp:"'You're looking bright' is a positive observation. Asking about it shows you notice and care. Light, friendly conversation."},
          {id:"st027",type:"error",q:"I don't know what to say to you. The weather is nice.",a:"Lovely day, isn't it? Makes me wish I was out there instead of marking!",exp:"'I don't know what to say to you' is awkward and honest but not appropriate. Australians use weather as a conversational bridge naturally, with humour."},
          {id:"st028",type:"fill",q:"Can you believe the ___ are already over? It feels like we only just got ___.",a:"holidays ... back",exp:"Post-holiday staffroom talk. 'Can you believe' expresses shared disbelief. 'Only just got back' = returned very recently."},
          {id:"st029",type:"fill",q:"Hey, I don't think we've met properly. I'm Yunshu — I teach ___ upstairs. What do you ___?",a:"Technology ... teach",exp:"Simple, natural introduction for new colleagues. Giving your name, subject, and location helps them place you. Asking what they teach shows interest."},
          {id:"st030",type:"open",q:"Write a natural greeting for when you see a colleague who has just returned from sick leave.",a:"Hey Sarah! Good to see you back. How are you feeling? We missed you — the staffroom wasn't the same without you. Don't overdo it on your first day back, yeah?",exp:"Warm, caring, light-hearted. 'How are you feeling?' shows concern. 'Don't overdo it' shows you care about their recovery. Avoids prying into their illness."}
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "responding-naturally",
        title: "Responding Naturally in Conversations",
        theory: "Natural responses involve back-channelling ('Yeah, right', 'Oh really?', 'That's great'), follow-up questions, and short personal contributions. Chinese speakers sometimes give overly brief responses ('Fine') or don't ask follow-up questions, which can seem disinterested.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"st031",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'I had the worst Year 9 class today.' What is the most natural response?",options:["That is unfortunate.","Oh no, what happened?","I do not care.","Interesting."],a:1,exp:"'Oh no, what happened?' shows empathy and invites them to share. 'That is unfortunate' is grammatically correct but sounds robotic. Natural responses include emotion."},
          {id:"st032",type:"fill",q:"Oh ___, that sounds awful! Did you manage to get them back on ___?",a:"no ... track",exp:"'Oh no' is an empathetic response. 'Get them back on track' = restore focus/behaviour. Asking a follow-up shows genuine interest."},
          {id:"st033",type:"error",q:"Colleague: 'I just got engaged!' You: 'Oh. That is good news. Congratulations.'",a:"Colleague: 'I just got engaged!' You: 'Oh my God, congratulations! That's amazing! When did it happen? Tell me everything!'",exp:"The original response is flat and unenthusiastic. Australian culture expects excited, warm responses to personal good news. Show genuine excitement with exclamations and questions."},
          {id:"st034",type:"fill",q:"Oh ___, that's brilliant! How long have you ___ together?",a:"wow ... been",exp:"'Oh wow' expresses excitement. 'How long have you been together?' is a natural follow-up question to relationship news. Shows you're engaged."},
          {id:"st035",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'I think I'm coming down with something.' What is the most helpful response?",options:["You should go home.","Oh no, there's something going around. Are you OK? Do you need anything?","That's not my problem.","Don't give it to me!"],a:1,exp:"'There's something going around' validates their concern. 'Are you OK? Do you need anything?' shows care. In Australian staffrooms, this kind of concern is expected and appreciated."},
          {id:"st036",type:"fill",q:"Tell me about it! I had the ___ experience with my Year 8s. They were completely off the ___.",a:"same ... planet",exp:"'Tell me about it!' = I totally relate/agree. 'Off the planet' = behaving wildly, completely unfocused. Sharing a similar experience builds connection."},
          {id:"st037",type:"fill",q:"That's so ___! I didn't know you were into ___. How long have you been doing it?",a:"cool ... that",exp:"'That's so cool!' shows genuine interest. Asking how long they've been doing something is a natural follow-up that keeps the conversation going."},
          {id:"st038",type:"error",q:"Colleague: 'My daughter just started university!' You: 'OK.'",a:"Colleague: 'My daughter just started university!' You: 'That's exciting! What's she studying? You must be so proud.'",exp:"'OK' is the bare minimum and sounds disinterested. In Australian conversation, personal milestones deserve an enthusiastic response with follow-up questions."},
          {id:"st039",type:"mc",q:"What is 'back-channelling' in conversation?",options:["Talking behind someone's back","Short verbal responses that show you're listening (yeah, mmm, right, oh really?)","Changing the topic","Speaking very quietly"],a:1,exp:"Back-channelling = the small verbal cues that show you're actively listening. 'Yeah', 'mmm', 'right', 'oh really?', 'I see'. Essential for natural conversation flow."},
          {id:"st040",type:"fill",q:"___ really? I had no idea! How did you ___ out about that?",a:"Oh ... find",exp:"'Oh really?' is a classic back-channel response showing surprise and interest. 'How did you find out?' is a natural follow-up."},
          {id:"st041",type:"fill",q:"That must have been so ___. How did you ___ with it?",a:"stressful ... deal",exp:"'That must have been so stressful' validates the other person's experience. 'How did you deal with it?' shows interest in their coping strategy."},
          {id:"st042",type:"mc",q:"A colleague shares that they're struggling with work-life balance. What is the most supportive response?",options:["That's your problem.","Yeah, it's really tough, isn't it? I feel the same way sometimes. Is there anything I can help with?","Just work harder.","You should get a different job."],a:1,exp:"Validating ('it's tough'), relating ('I feel the same'), and offering help. This is supportive, empathetic, and doesn't judge. Exactly what good colleague communication looks like."},
          {id:"st043",type:"fill",q:"No ___! That's so funny. Something similar happened to me last ___.",a:"way ... term",exp:"'No way!' expresses surprise/disbelief. Sharing a related experience ('Something similar happened to me') builds connection and keeps conversation going."},
          {id:"st044",type:"error",q:"Colleague: 'I ran a half marathon on the weekend!' You: 'Oh. Is it?'",a:"Colleague: 'I ran a half marathon on the weekend!' You: 'Wow, that's amazing! How did you go? What was your time?'",exp:"'Oh. Is it?' makes no sense as a response and sounds confused. Show enthusiasm for their achievement and ask specific questions."},
          {id:"st045",type:"fill",q:"I completely ___ what you mean. I had a similar ___ with my Year 10 class last year.",a:"know ... issue",exp:"'I completely know what you mean' shows understanding and empathy. Sharing a parallel experience shows you relate to their situation."},
          {id:"st046",type:"fill",q:"That's a really good ___. I hadn't thought about it that ___.",a:"point ... way",exp:"'That's a really good point' validates the other person's contribution. 'I hadn't thought about it that way' shows openness and respect for their perspective."},
          {id:"st047",type:"mc",q:"How can you show you're actively listening in a staffroom conversation?",options:["Look at your phone while they talk","Nod, make eye contact, and use phrases like 'yeah', 'right', 'I see'","Interrupt with your own story immediately","Turn away to make coffee while they talk"],a:1,exp:"Active listening involves eye contact, nodding, and verbal cues. These non-verbal and verbal signals tell the speaker you're engaged and care about what they're saying."},
          {id:"st048",type:"fill",q:"Fair ___, I suppose that makes sense. I just think it could have been handled ___.",a:"enough ... differently",exp:"'Fair enough' is a very Australian way of acknowledging someone's point even if you slightly disagree. It's conceding without fully agreeing."},
          {id:"st049",type:"open",q:"A colleague tells you they just bought a house. Write a natural, enthusiastic response.",a:"Oh my God, congratulations! That's such exciting news! Where is it? How long have you been looking? You must be over the moon. We should celebrate — I'll bring cake to the staffroom!",exp:"Multiple exclamations, follow-up questions (where, how long), an idiom ('over the moon' = very happy), and an offer to celebrate. This is the warmth Australian colleagues expect."},
          {id:"st050",type:"fill",q:"Oh, that ___ me — did you hear about the new car park ___?",a:"reminds ... rules",exp:"'Oh, that reminds me' is a natural topic transition. It connects what they said to something related, keeping conversation flowing."},
          {id:"st051",type:"error",q:"Colleague: 'I'm so tired today.' You: 'Why?'",a:"Colleague: 'I'm so tired today.' You: 'Same! Rough night? I was up until midnight marking. These reports are killing me.'",exp:"Bare 'Why?' sounds interrogative and cold. A natural response empathises, shares your own experience, and uses casual language. 'Killing me' = figuratively overwhelming."},
          {id:"st052",type:"fill",q:"Honestly, I'm not ___. I saw that coming from a mile ___.",a:"surprised ... away",exp:"'I'm not surprised' and 'saw it coming from a mile away' show you anticipated something. 'From a mile away' = very obviously predictable."},
          {id:"st053",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'I reckon we should push back the due date.' What does 'reckon' mean?",options:["Calculate mathematically","Think/believe (Australian informal)","Demand","Refuse"],a:1,exp:"'Reckon' is very Australian and means 'think' or 'believe'. 'I reckon' = 'I think'. It's informal but perfectly appropriate in staffroom conversation."},
          {id:"st054",type:"fill",q:"You're ___ me! That actually happened? I can't believe ___!",a:"kidding ... it",exp:"'You're kidding me!' expresses disbelief/shock. 'I can't believe it!' reinforces the surprise. Natural, animated response to unexpected news."},
          {id:"st055",type:"fill",q:"Yeah, ___ about it. The staffroom fridge is a ___ zone. Nobody ever cleans it.",a:"don't ... war",exp:"'Tell me about it' or 'don't talk about it' = I totally agree. 'War zone' is humorous hyperbole for a messy shared space. Classic staffroom complaint."},
          {id:"st056",type:"fill",q:"Good on ___! That takes a lot of courage. I'm really ___ for you.",a:"you ... happy",exp:"'Good on you!' is a very Australian expression meaning 'well done/I'm proud of you'. Shows admiration and support for someone's achievement or decision."},
          {id:"st057",type:"mc",q:"What does 'You're telling me!' mean as a response?",options:["Please explain more","I strongly agree — I feel the same way","I don't believe you","You should stop talking"],a:1,exp:"'You're telling me!' is an emphatic agreement. It means 'I completely know what you mean — I feel exactly the same way.' It's enthusiastic and relatable."},
          {id:"st058",type:"fill",q:"That's ___ of you to say. I really ___ the kind words.",a:"sweet ... appreciate",exp:"Accepting compliments gracefully is important. 'That's sweet of you' and 'I appreciate the kind words' are warm, genuine acknowledgements."},
          {id:"st059",type:"fill",q:"Sounds like you've had a rough ___. Do you want to grab a ___ after school?",a:"trot ... drink",exp:"'Rough trot' is Australian for a difficult period. 'Grab a drink' (could be coffee or something stronger) is an offer of companionship and support."},
          {id:"st060",type:"error",q:"Colleague: 'I got promoted!' You: 'Good. You deserve.'",a:"Colleague: 'I got promoted!' You: 'That's fantastic — you absolutely deserve it! Well done! When do you start?'",exp:"'Good' is too flat. 'You deserve' needs 'it' (you deserve it). In Australian culture, promotions deserve enthusiastic celebration with exclamations and questions."}
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "opinions-agreeing",
        title: "Sharing Opinions & Agreeing/Disagreeing",
        theory: "In Australian staffrooms, opinions are shared casually but disagreement should be gentle. 'I see what you mean, but...', 'That's a good point, although...', 'I'm not sure about that because...' are all natural. Chinese speakers sometimes avoid disagreeing entirely or disagree too bluntly.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"st061",type:"fill",q:"I see what you ___, but I think we might need to look at it from a different ___.",a:"mean ... angle",exp:"'I see what you mean, but...' is the classic Australian soft disagreement. It validates first, then offers an alternative. 'Different angle' = different perspective."},
          {id:"st062",type:"mc",q:"Which is the most natural way to disagree with a colleague's teaching idea?",options:["That's a terrible idea.","Hmm, I see where you're coming from, but I wonder if it might be tricky with our year group. What if we tried...","No. Wrong.","I respectfully submit that your idea has limitations."],a:1,exp:"Acknowledges their perspective, raises a concern gently ('I wonder if'), and offers an alternative. This is how collegial disagreement works in Australia."},
          {id:"st063",type:"fill",q:"That's a fair ___. I hadn't ___ of it that way before.",a:"point ... thought",exp:"'That's a fair point' acknowledges the validity of their argument. 'I hadn't thought of it that way' shows intellectual openness."},
          {id:"st064",type:"error",q:"I am not agree with you. Your idea is not practical.",a:"I'm not sure I agree. I think it might be difficult to implement in practice — what do you think?",exp:"'Am not agree' — should be 'don't agree'. 'Your idea is not practical' is too blunt. Soften with 'I'm not sure' and invite further discussion."},
          {id:"st065",type:"fill",q:"You might be ___ to something there. Let me ___ about it and get back to you.",a:"on ... think",exp:"'You might be on to something' = your idea might have merit. 'Let me think about it' buys time without committing or rejecting."},
          {id:"st066",type:"mc",q:"A colleague strongly disagrees with a school policy and you agree with the policy. What is the best response?",options:["You're wrong and the principal is right.","I can understand why you feel that way. I personally think the policy has some merit, although I agree it could be refined.","Just accept it.","I have no opinion."],a:1,exp:"Validates their feelings, shares your different opinion respectfully, and finds common ground. This maintains the relationship while being honest."},
          {id:"st067",type:"fill",q:"I totally ___! That's exactly what I've been trying to ___ for weeks.",a:"agree ... say",exp:"'I totally agree!' is an enthusiastic agreement. 'That's exactly what I've been trying to say' validates both parties. Strong, positive affirmation."},
          {id:"st068",type:"fill",q:"I take your ___, but I'm not entirely ___ it would work with our students.",a:"point ... convinced",exp:"'I take your point' = I understand your argument. 'Not entirely convinced' is a polite way to express doubt without being dismissive."},
          {id:"st069",type:"error",q:"I don't think so. You are wrong about this matter. The correct answer is what I said.",a:"I'm not sure I see it the same way. I think there might be a few things to consider. Can I explain my thinking?",exp:"Too blunt and arrogant. 'You are wrong' is confrontational. 'Can I explain my thinking?' invites dialogue rather than shutting it down."},
          {id:"st070",type:"mc",q:"What does 'each to their own' mean?",options:["Everyone should have their own classroom","Everyone is entitled to their own opinion/preference — I accept your choice even if I disagree","Each teacher must do their own marking","Everyone owns something"],a:1,exp:"'Each to their own' (Australian/British version of 'to each their own') means you accept someone's different preference without judging. It's a graceful way to end a mild disagreement."},
          {id:"st071",type:"fill",q:"I'm in two ___ about that. On one ___, it could work, but on the other, it might create more problems.",a:"minds ... hand",exp:"'In two minds' = undecided. 'On one hand... on the other' presents both sides. Honest about uncertainty without dismissing the idea."},
          {id:"st072",type:"fill",q:"That's a great suggestion, ___. I reckon that could really make a ___ to how we run the program.",a:"actually ... difference",exp:"'That's a great suggestion, actually' — 'actually' here shows mild surprise and genuine appreciation. 'Make a difference' = have a positive impact."},
          {id:"st073",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'I reckon homework is pointless.' You disagree but want to be diplomatic. Which response is best?",options:["That's ridiculous.","I see where you're coming from — I sometimes wonder about it too. I reckon it depends on the type of homework, though. Short, meaningful tasks seem to help my students.","You clearly don't care about education.","Maybe."],a:1,exp:"Acknowledges their view, admits your own doubts, then gently offers a nuanced counter-argument with evidence. This is respectful, collaborative discussion."},
          {id:"st074",type:"fill",q:"Look, I hear what you're saying, but from my ___, it's a bit more ___ than that.",a:"experience ... complicated",exp:"'I hear what you're saying' validates. 'From my experience' grounds your view in evidence. 'A bit more complicated' gently introduces complexity."},
          {id:"st075",type:"fill",q:"I couldn't agree ___! That's been my biggest ___ about the new system too.",a:"more ... frustration",exp:"'I couldn't agree more!' is the strongest form of agreement. Sharing the same frustration builds solidarity."},
          {id:"st076",type:"error",q:"I think maybe possibly perhaps we could consider thinking about changing the system.",a:"I reckon we should look at changing the system.",exp:"Massively over-hedged. Four hedging words ('maybe possibly perhaps could consider') make you sound uncertain and lacking confidence. In Australia, one hedge is enough."},
          {id:"st077",type:"fill",q:"To be ___ with you, I'm not a huge ___ of the new timetable either.",a:"honest ... fan",exp:"'To be honest with you' signals candour. 'Not a huge fan of' is a soft way to say you dislike something. Direct but not aggressive."},
          {id:"st078",type:"mc",q:"When should you avoid sharing your opinion in a staffroom?",options:["Never — always share","When the topic involves confidential student information, another teacher's performance review, or sensitive personal matters about a colleague","Only on Mondays","When you disagree with the majority"],a:1,exp:"Professional boundaries matter. Opinions about confidential student matters, colleague evaluations, or sensitive personal information should be kept private."},
          {id:"st079",type:"fill",q:"I think we're on the same ___ here. Let's ___ up a plan and take it to the meeting.",a:"page ... draw",exp:"'On the same page' = in agreement. 'Draw up a plan' = create a plan together. Moving from agreement to action shows initiative."},
          {id:"st080",type:"open",q:"A colleague says 'I think we should ban phones completely in school.' You partly agree. Write a natural response.",a:"Yeah, I get where you're coming from — phones can definitely be a massive distraction. I'm not sure a complete ban would work, though. Some teachers use them really well for research and apps. Maybe we could have them locked away during lessons but available at break? I reckon a middle ground might work better.",exp:"Acknowledges their point, expresses partial agreement, explains the nuance, and offers a compromise. Uses natural hedging ('I'm not sure', 'I reckon', 'might work')."},
          {id:"st081",type:"fill",q:"Fair ___. I still think there's room for ___, but I see your point.",a:"enough ... improvement",exp:"'Fair enough' concedes their argument without fully agreeing. 'Room for improvement' is a diplomatic way to say something isn't perfect yet."},
          {id:"st082",type:"fill",q:"You know what, you've ___ changed my mind. I hadn't looked at it from that ___ before.",a:"actually ... perspective",exp:"Being willing to change your mind is valued in Australian culture. 'You've actually changed my mind' is honest and shows intellectual flexibility."},
          {id:"st083",type:"mc",q:"What does 'she'll be right' mean in Australian culture?",options:["She is correct","The woman is fine","It will be OK / don't worry about it","She will turn right"],a:2,exp:"'She'll be right' is a classic Australian expression meaning 'it will work out' or 'don't worry about it'. It reflects the Australian laid-back attitude."},
          {id:"st084",type:"fill",q:"I'm with you on ___. The current system isn't working and we need to ___ something different.",a:"that ... try",exp:"'I'm with you on that' = I agree with your position. 'Need to try something different' focuses on action."},
          {id:"st085",type:"error",q:"In my humble opinion, I would like to politely suggest that perhaps we might want to possibly think about modifying the approach.",a:"I reckon we should tweak the approach a bit. What do you think?",exp:"Way too many hedges. Australian English values directness within politeness. 'I reckon' + one simple suggestion + inviting feedback is much more natural."},
          {id:"st086",type:"fill",q:"I have ___ feelings about that. Part of me thinks it's great, but another part ___.",a:"mixed ... worries me",exp:"'Mixed feelings' is honest. 'Part of me thinks... but another part...' shows nuanced thinking and invites further discussion."},
          {id:"st087",type:"fill",q:"Let's agree to ___. We clearly see this ___, and that's OK.",a:"disagree ... differently",exp:"'Agree to disagree' is a mature way to end a disagreement without animosity. It acknowledges the difference and moves on."},
          {id:"st088",type:"mc",q:"What does 'I'm not fussed' mean?",options:["I'm angry","I don't have a preference — either option is fine","I'm confused","I'm offended"],a:1,exp:"'I'm not fussed' is Australian for 'I don't mind either way' or 'I have no strong preference'. Very useful when asked to choose between options."},
          {id:"st089",type:"fill",q:"That's an interesting take. I wouldn't have thought of it ___ way, but it ___.",a:"that ... works",exp:"'Interesting take' validates without fully agreeing. 'I wouldn't have thought of it that way' shows you're open. 'But it works' concedes their approach has value."},
          {id:"st090",type:"fill",q:"Spot ___! That's exactly ___. You've nailed it.",a:"on ... right",exp:"'Spot on' is very Australian/British for 'exactly correct'. 'You've nailed it' = you got it exactly right. Strong, enthusiastic agreement."}
        ]
      },
      {
        id: "weekend-plans-hobbies",
        title: "Talking About Plans, Weekends & Hobbies",
        theory: "Talking about personal life builds collegial relationships. Australian colleagues commonly discuss weekends, holidays, sport, food, family activities, and TV shows. Chinese speakers sometimes feel this is too personal, but in Australia it's expected and builds trust.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"st091",type:"fill",q:"Any plans for the ___? We're thinking of heading to the ___ if the weather holds up.",a:"weekend ... beach",exp:"'Any plans for the weekend?' is the most common Friday question. 'Heading to the beach' is quintessentially Australian. 'If the weather holds up' = if it stays nice."},
          {id:"st092",type:"mc",q:"A colleague asks about your weekend. Which is the most natural response?",options:["My weekend was characterised by domestic responsibilities.","Pretty quiet, actually. Just caught up on some marking and took the kids to the park. How about you?","It was fine.","I engaged in leisure activities."],a:1,exp:"Natural, specific, casual. 'Pretty quiet, actually' is a common low-key opener. Mentioning specific activities and asking back is essential for conversation flow."},
          {id:"st093",type:"fill",q:"We had a ___ one this weekend. Just stayed in, watched some ___, and caught up on sleep.",a:"lazy ... Netflix",exp:"'A lazy one' is a natural way to describe a relaxed weekend. Mentioning Netflix and sleep is relatable. Australians are comfortable admitting to quiet weekends."},
          {id:"st094",type:"error",q:"I didn't do anything special. Just study and rest. I don't have hobby.",a:"Not much, really. Just caught up on some study and had a bit of a rest. I've been getting into cooking lately, actually.",exp:"'I don't have hobby' — 'I don't have a hobby' or 'hobbies'. More importantly, try to add something personal to keep conversation going rather than giving a dead-end response."},
          {id:"st095",type:"fill",q:"Oh nice, you went ___ on the weekend? That sounds amazing. Where did you ___?",a:"camping ... go",exp:"Showing interest in a colleague's activities. 'That sounds amazing' is a warm response. Follow-up questions keep the conversation going naturally."},
          {id:"st096",type:"mc",q:"A colleague mentions they went to the footy on the weekend. In Australia, 'the footy' most likely refers to:",options:["Football (soccer) only","Rugby League or AFL depending on the state","American football","Table football"],a:1,exp:"In NSW, 'the footy' usually means Rugby League (NRL). In Victoria and other states, it usually means AFL. Context and state matter. Going to 'the footy' is a major Australian social activity."},
          {id:"st097",type:"fill",q:"Have you been watching anything good ___? I need a new show to ___.",a:"lately ... binge",exp:"Discussing TV shows is common staffroom talk. 'Anything good lately?' is a natural way to ask. 'Binge' = watch many episodes in a row. Very current language."},
          {id:"st098",type:"fill",q:"We took the kids to Luna ___ on Saturday. It was packed, but they had a ___.",a:"Park ... blast",exp:"'Luna Park' is a famous Sydney attraction. 'Had a blast' = had a wonderful time. Sharing family activities is normal and expected."},
          {id:"st099",type:"error",q:"I like to play the basketball on weekend. It is my favourite sport activity.",a:"I play basketball on weekends. It's my favourite sport.",exp:"No 'the' before 'basketball' (sports don't take articles). 'On weekend' needs 'on weekends' (plural for habitual). 'Sport activity' is redundant — just 'sport'."},
          {id:"st100",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'We're heading up the coast this long weekend.' What does 'up the coast' mean?",options:["Going to the mountains","Travelling north along the coastline for a holiday","Going to a coastal city for work","Swimming in the ocean"],a:1,exp:"'Up the coast' (or 'down the coast') means travelling along the coastline for a holiday or getaway. Long weekends are prime time for coastal trips in Australia."},
          {id:"st101",type:"fill",q:"I've just started getting into ___. A friend talked me into ___ and now I'm hooked!",a:"yoga ... trying it",exp:"'Getting into' = starting to enjoy. 'Talked me into' = persuaded me. 'Hooked' = addicted/really enjoying it. Natural hobby conversation."},
          {id:"st102",type:"fill",q:"That new Thai place on Church Street is ___. Have you been ___? The pad thai is incredible.",a:"amazing ... yet",exp:"Recommending restaurants is classic staffroom talk, especially near schools. 'Have you been yet?' invites them to try it."},
          {id:"st103",type:"error",q:"The weekend I went to the friend house for eating dinner. The food is very delicious.",a:"On the weekend I went to a friend's place for dinner. The food was amazing.",exp:"'The weekend' needs 'On'. 'The friend house' — 'a friend's place' (possessive, 'place' is more natural than 'house'). 'For eating' — 'for dinner'. 'Is' should be 'was'. 'Delicious' is fine but 'amazing' is more natural in casual speech."},
          {id:"st104",type:"fill",q:"Are you doing anything for the long ___? I was thinking about heading down to the South ___ for a few days.",a:"weekend ... Coast",exp:"Long weekends are widely discussed. 'Heading down to the South Coast' is a common NSW getaway plan. Shows regional knowledge."},
          {id:"st105",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says they spent the weekend 'pottering around the house.' What does this mean?",options:["Making pottery","Doing small, leisurely tasks at home without a specific plan","Gardening only","Cleaning the house thoroughly"],a:1,exp:"'Pottering around' (Australian/British) means doing small, unhurried tasks at home — a bit of gardening, tidying, cooking. It implies a relaxed, unstructured day."},
          {id:"st106",type:"fill",q:"I'm counting down the ___ until the holidays. I think I need a break more than the ___ do!",a:"days ... kids",exp:"'Counting down the days' shows anticipation. The joke about teachers needing holidays more than students is a universal staffroom favourite."},
          {id:"st107",type:"fill",q:"You should come along next time! It's really ___ and a good way to ___ after a long week.",a:"fun ... unwind",exp:"Inviting colleagues to activities builds relationships. 'Come along' = join us. 'Unwind' = relax after stress."},
          {id:"st108",type:"open",q:"A colleague asks 'How was your weekend?' Write a natural, engaging response that keeps the conversation going.",a:"Yeah, it was really nice, actually. We went to the Powerhouse Museum on Saturday — they've got this new exhibit on space exploration which was pretty cool. Then Sunday was all about meal prepping for the week, which sounds boring but I'm trying to eat better. How about you — did you get up to much?",exp:"Specific activities, a mix of interesting and mundane, self-deprecating humour, and returning the question. This is how Australians keep conversations flowing naturally."},
          {id:"st109",type:"fill",q:"I've been meaning to check that out! Is it ___ the trip? How long does it ___ to get there?",a:"worth ... take",exp:"'Worth the trip' = is the journey justified by what's there? 'How long does it take?' is a practical follow-up. Shows you're genuinely considering going."},
          {id:"st110",type:"mc",q:"A colleague mentions they spent the weekend at Bunnings. In Australia, this most likely means they:",options:["Went to a technology store","Went to a hardware/home improvement store — probably doing a home project","Went to a sports store","Went to a bookshop"],a:1,exp:"Bunnings is Australia's iconic hardware store. Spending the weekend at Bunnings is a beloved Australian cliche — it means DIY home projects and, of course, a Bunnings sausage sizzle."},
          {id:"st111",type:"fill",q:"We had a barbecue on Sunday with some ___ and neighbours. The weather was ___, so we stayed outside all afternoon.",a:"friends ... perfect",exp:"Barbecues are central to Australian social life. 'Friends and neighbours' is a classic gathering. 'Stayed outside all afternoon' paints a relaxed picture."},
          {id:"st112",type:"fill",q:"I've taken up ___ recently. It's harder than it looks, but I'm really ___ it.",a:"surfing ... enjoying",exp:"'Taken up' = started a new hobby. Surfing is quintessentially Australian. 'Harder than it looks' is an honest, relatable admission."},
          {id:"st113",type:"error",q:"On the holiday I went to the Melbourne to visit my the relative. The trip was very tire.",a:"Over the holidays I went to Melbourne to visit some relatives. The trip was exhausting but really enjoyable.",exp:"No 'the' before city names. 'My the relative' — 'some relatives'. 'Very tire' — 'exhausting' (adjective). Also add something positive to make conversation more engaging."},
          {id:"st114",type:"fill",q:"Did you catch the cricket last night? What a ___! I couldn't believe that last ___.",a:"match ... over",exp:"'Did you catch' = did you watch. Cricket talk is essential Australian staffroom content. 'Over' is a cricket term (six balls bowled). Shows cultural integration."},
          {id:"st115",type:"mc",q:"What does 'arvo' mean in Australian English?",options:["A type of plant","Afternoon","A greeting","Morning"],a:1,exp:"'Arvo' is Australian slang for 'afternoon'. 'This arvo' = this afternoon. 'Saturday arvo' = Saturday afternoon. Extremely common in casual conversation."},
          {id:"st116",type:"fill",q:"I'm thinking of signing up for a ___ class. There's one at the community ___ on Wednesday evenings.",a:"pottery ... centre",exp:"Discussing plans to take up new hobbies is natural. 'Community centre' is Australian English (not 'center'). Wednesday evenings are a common class time."},
          {id:"st117",type:"fill",q:"We're planning a big trip to ___ during the July holidays. It'll be our first time going ___.",a:"Japan ... overseas",exp:"'July holidays' = Term 2 break. Discussing holiday plans is very common. 'Going overseas' = travelling internationally."},
          {id:"st118",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'I'm flat out this weekend — we're moving house.' What is an appropriate response?",options:["That sounds boring.","Oh wow, big weekend! Do you need a hand with anything?","Why?","Moving is easy."],a:1,exp:"'Big weekend!' acknowledges the effort. 'Do you need a hand?' is a generous, typically Australian offer of help. 'Need a hand' = need help."},
          {id:"st119",type:"fill",q:"I finally finished reading that book you ___. You were right — it was absolutely ___!",a:"recommended ... brilliant",exp:"Following up on a recommendation strengthens the relationship. 'You were right' validates their taste. 'Absolutely brilliant' is enthusiastic praise."},
          {id:"st120",type:"fill",q:"We should organise a staff ___ night sometime. I reckon it'd be a great way to get everyone together outside of ___.",a:"trivia ... school",exp:"Suggesting social activities shows initiative. 'Trivia night' (pub quiz) is extremely popular in Australia. 'Outside of school' = in a social context."}
        ]
      }
    ]
  };

})();
